title: For Sale:  GG&G Under Foregaurd Integrated Rail (UFIR)
location: Panama City Beach, Panama City, Florida
postcontent:
100% US MADE!!! Convert standard AR-15 foreguard into Picatinny rail system

Vertical foregrips and other accessories mounted at the 6 o'clock position on shoulder fired weapons have become prominent in military, law enforcement and civilian arenas. However, not every agency or individual for that matter, can afford or justify the purchase of a forearm assembly surrounded by multiple rails, when all they want to do is add a vertical foregrip or flashlight to the weapon.

Over ten years ago, GG&G introduced an inexpensive but mission ready Under Forearm Integrated Rail (UFIR) that permits instant installation and removal of most vertical foregrips, flashlights and numerous other accessories on the AR15/M16 weapon systems. This adapter rail can easily be installed onto the underside of an AR15 or M16 forearm, (standard or M4), using simple hand tools and a small amount of Loctite 262. The three point mounting system insures a solid, rugged mounting platform. Because our handguard rail mount follows the Picatinny Rail (MIL-STD-1913 or NATO's STANAG 2324) standard you will have no problem with accessory compatibility.

Installation does not require permanent alteration to the forearm. Detailed instructions and all of the parts required are supplied in the kit. The UFIR is manufactured from solid 6061 T6 billet aluminum alloy and is Type III hard-coat anodized matte black per mil-spec to provide combat durability. The GG&G UFIR is four inches long, provides eleven mounting cross lugs and machined to MIL-STD-1913 specifications so as to provide tactical flexibility in accessory mounting. It is lightweight too-at only 1.6 ounces.

Link to mfg:
http://www.gggaz.com/ar-15-m16-under-forearm-integrated-rail-ufir.html

Up for sale is a hard to find Winchester Model 69.  This gun was manufactured from 1935-1963.  This exact rifle was made around 1935-1946 based on the shape of the stock.  The Model 69 does not come with serial numbers so there is no accurate way to find the exact date of production.  The wood stock is in great shape with a few small dings in it from wear and tear.  The barrel is in good shape with orginal sights on the front and rear.
